         <div>
            <head>24.5.1884 Samstag</head>
            <p>
               <placeName type="write" key="49069">Hamburg</placeName>. May 24. 1884. Saturday</p>
            <p>Did not go to school till 10 today as <persName key="1322">Rautenberg</persName> and
                  <persName key="1222">Ballheimer</persName> are still ill. I found out that
                  <persName key="1325">Kohlmann</persName> is an atheist, and an atheist whose whole
               system of morals is based on monstrous egoïsm and selfworship. I never heard anything
               so preposterous as his theories, I really could not help laughing at them and his
               conceit. He told me he thought himself much better off than we Christians and than
               anybody who believed in a God for he felt certainty while we can not. Next to this
               conceit there was a vein of cowardliness which was revolting. He was frightened to
               death lest I should tell anybody he was an atheist; he denies everything better and
               higher than man, life after death, punishment for our sins in fact everything except
               what he can see and feel. The conversation interested me much as I had never talked
               with a real atheist before. I am glad to say he made no impression whatsoever on my
               mind. Got a letter from <persName key="176">Papa</persName>.</p>
         </div>
